# Post-Deployment PROD Verification — Runbook

Run **after** the prod deploy + Route53 URL change. Ordered as a live smoke test: verify the thing that just changed (DNS/URL) first, then work edge → app → data → user journey.

> ⚠️ **This is production and the portal actuates real appliances. Everything here is READ-ONLY.** Do **not** send control commands, do **not** run resilience/failover tests, do **not** write data as part of this verification. Deeper per-domain checks live in the EKS / AWS-services / UI references — this runbook cross-references them.

Set your variables once:
```bash
export URL=<new-portal-hostname>        # e.g. portal.example.com (the newly changed Route53 record)
export NS=<prod-namespace>
export START=$(date -u -d '20 min ago' +%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%SZ)   # macOS: date -u -v-20M ...
export END=$(date -u +%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%SZ)
```

---

## 0. Confirm you're in PROD (do this first)

```bash
aws sts get-caller-identity            # correct prod account?
kubectl config current-context         # correct prod cluster?
```

If either isn't unmistakably production, stop and fix your context before continuing.

---

## 1. DNS / Route 53 — the change you just made

```bash
# What the record is actually set to
aws route53 list-hosted-zones --query 'HostedZones[*].{Name:Name,Id:Id}'
aws route53 list-resource-record-sets --hosted-zone-id <zone-id> \
  --query "ResourceRecordSets[?Name=='${URL}.'].{Name:Name,Type:Type,TTL:TTL,Alias:AliasTarget.DNSName,Records:ResourceRecords}"

# Does it resolve, and to what?
dig +short $URL
nslookup $URL

# Propagation check — query public resolvers, not just your local cache
dig +short $URL @8.8.8.8
dig +short $URL @1.1.1.1
```

**Look for:** the record present with the **expected alias target** (CloudFront distribution domain or ALB DNS); it resolves **consistently across resolvers** (propagation complete); TTL is sane. If resolvers disagree, propagation is still in flight — wait out the old TTL before trusting downstream checks.

---

## 2. TLS on the new hostname

```bash
# Cert served on the new URL: subject/SAN match, issuer, expiry
echo | openssl s_client -servername $URL -connect $URL:443 2>/dev/null \
  | openssl x509 -noout -subject -issuer -dates -ext subjectAltName
```

**Look for:** the SAN list **includes the new hostname**; `notAfter` comfortably in the future; trusted issuer; handshake succeeds with no warning. A mismatched SAN is the classic post-rename failure.

---

## 3. Edge reachability — CloudFront + ALB

```bash
# CloudFront: deployed, enabled, and carrying the new alias
aws cloudfront list-distributions \
  --query "DistributionList.Items[?contains(Aliases.Items, '${URL}')].{Id:Id,Status:Status,Enabled:Enabled,Domain:DomainName}"

# ALB targets healthy behind the scenes
aws elbv2 describe-target-health --target-group-arn <tg-arn> \
  --query 'TargetHealthDescriptions[*].{Target:Target.Id,State:TargetHealth.State,Reason:TargetHealth.Reason}'

# Does the app actually serve at the new URL? (follow redirects, show timing)
curl -sSL -o /dev/null -w 'HTTP %{http_code}  time %{time_total}s  redirects %{num_redirects}\n' https://$URL

# HTTP must redirect to HTTPS
curl -sSI http://$URL | grep -iE 'HTTP/|location'
```

**Look for:** distribution `Deployed` + `Enabled` with the new alias; **all ALB targets `healthy`**; `HTTP 200` from the new URL; HTTP→HTTPS redirect working.

---

## 4. Confirm the RIGHT build is live (not a cached old one)

```bash
# Version endpoint or build hash, whichever the app exposes
curl -sS https://$URL/version 2>/dev/null || true
curl -sS https://$URL | grep -oE 'build[-_/][a-z0-9]+' | head

# Security/cache headers on the new URL
curl -sSI https://$URL | grep -iE \
 'strict-transport-security|content-security-policy|x-frame-options|x-content-type-options|cache-control|x-cache'
```

**Look for:** version/build string matches **the release you just deployed** — a stale build here means CloudFront is serving a cached old version (invalidate if so). `x-cache` reveals hit/miss from the edge.

---

## 5. Kubernetes workload health (read-only)

```bash
kubectl get pods -n $NS -o wide
kubectl get pods -n $NS --sort-by='.status.containerStatuses[0].restartCount'
kubectl get deploy -n $NS -o custom-columns=\
NAME:.metadata.name,DESIRED:.spec.replicas,READY:.status.readyReplicas,AVAIL:.status.availableReplicas

# Images running = intended release
kubectl get pods -n $NS -o jsonpath='{.items[*].spec.containers[*].image}' | tr ' ' '\n' | sort -u

# ArgoCD synced & healthy to the release
kubectl get applications -n argocd -o custom-columns=\
NAME:.metadata.name,SYNC:.status.sync.status,HEALTH:.status.health.status
```

**Look for:** no CrashLoop/ImagePull, low restart counts, `DESIRED == READY == AVAIL`, images match the release tag/digest, all Argo apps **Synced + Healthy**.

---

## 6. Per-service health (read-only, in-cluster)

```bash
# Actuator health for each API pod (adjust selector/port/path)
for p in $(kubectl get pods -n $NS -l <selector> -o name); do
  echo "== $p =="; kubectl exec $p -n $NS -- curl -s localhost:8080/actuator/health | jq -c .
done
```

Confirm: **OAuth API** healthy and its signing keys reachable; **main data/control API** shows its `db` component `UP`; **Stream API** healthy.

---

## 7. Real-time (SSE) through the new URL

```bash
# End-to-end stream via the new hostname — confirm events flow AND the connection stays open
curl -N --max-time 30 https://$URL/<sse-path>
```

**Look for:** events arrive and the connection **stays open** through the edge (idle-timeout / buffering not killing it). Ctrl-C once you've seen events flow. This is the check most likely to behave differently in prod than lower envs.

---

## 8. Data layer (read-only)

```bash
aws rds describe-db-instances --db-instance-identifier <id> \
  --query 'DBInstances[0].{Status:DBInstanceStatus,MultiAZ:MultiAZ}'
aws elasticache describe-replication-groups --replication-group-id <id> \
  --query 'ReplicationGroups[0].{Status:Status,AutoFailover:AutomaticFailover}'

# Kafka consumer lag near zero (from a pod/bastion with the CLI tools)
kafka-consumer-groups.sh --bootstrap-server <bootstrap> --describe --group <group>   # LAG column
```

**Look for:** RDS + Redis `available`; **consumer lag near zero and not climbing** on the account/queue handlers.

---

## 9. Post-cutover error signal

```bash
# Anything firing right after the switch?
aws cloudwatch describe-alarms --state-value ALARM --query 'MetricAlarms[*].AlarmName'

# ALB 5xx since the cutover
aws cloudwatch get-metric-statistics --namespace AWS/ApplicationELB \
  --metric-name HTTPCode_Target_5XX_Count \
  --dimensions Name=LoadBalancer,Value=<lb-id> \
  --start-time $START --end-time $END --period 60 --statistics Sum

# Fresh app-log errors post-deploy
kubectl logs -n $NS -l <selector> --since=15m | grep -iE 'error|exception|fatal' | tail -30
```

**Look for:** no new alarms in `ALARM`; **no 5xx spike** correlated with the cutover time; no flood of new exceptions in the logs.

---

## 10. User-journey smoke test — browser, READ-ONLY

Walk the path against the **new URL**, confirming each hop, **without sending any control command to a live device**:

1. Load `https://$URL` → correct app, HTTPS, no console errors.
2. **OAuth login** redirect works → land on dashboard.
3. **Device list** loads (RBAC: only permitted devices visible).
4. Open a **device detail** → current state shows.
5. **Live state update** arrives via SSE without a manual refresh.

> **Do not issue control commands to real customer appliances as part of prod verification.** If the control path must be validated, use a **designated test device** per the UI checklist — never a live customer device.

---

## Rollback trigger

If DNS points wrong, the wrong build is served and won't invalidate, targets are unhealthy, a 5xx spike tracks the cutover, or the control/auth path misbehaves — **revert the Route53 record to the previous target** (or roll back via ArgoCD) per your runbook rather than debugging live. Capture pass/fail + evidence for each section as your go/no-go record.
